{{Han etym}}

In the oracle bone script and early bronze inscriptions, it was originally {{zh-l|*秂}}, an {{Han compound|禾|人|ls=ic|ls2=psc|c1=s|c2=p|t1=wheat; grain|t2=person|nocap=y}} – a person carrying wheat on his back – harvest.

In bronze inscriptions after the {{w|Western Zhou}} period, a stroke was often added to {{zh-l|*人}} to give {{och-l|千}}, which still acted as a phonetic component, and this form ({{zh-l|*秊}}) was inherited by later scripts. The current form is inherited from the clerical script, where ''libian'' ({{zh-l|*隸變}}) has occurred.

